542
00:21:36,090 --> 00:21:39,150
double blind peer-reviewed
studies conducted in humans

543
00:21:39,150 --> 00:21:41,640
that indicate that for instance,

544
00:21:41,640 --> 00:21:44,280
nicotine can reduce penile girth,

545
00:21:44,280 --> 00:21:45,480
that is the girth of the penis,

546
00:21:45,480 --> 00:21:48,720
and can lead to certain
forms of sexual dysfunction.

547
00:21:48,720 --> 00:21:51,900
And those changes are
largely downstream of changes

548
00:21:51,900 --> 00:21:55,020
in blood flow and
endothelial cell function.

549
00:21:55,020 --> 00:21:57,750
Endothelial cells are the cells
that make up blood vessels

550
00:21:57,750 --> 00:22:00,960
and other vascular type tissues
within the brain and body.

551
00:22:00,960 --> 00:22:03,000
So nicotine is found in these plants.

552
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:05,460
And what we can know for sure is

553
00:22:05,460 --> 00:22:07,980
that at some point in human evolution,

554
00:22:07,980 --> 00:22:09,960
somebody or some group of people,

555
00:22:09,960 --> 00:22:12,360
either, and here, I'm completely guessing,

556
00:22:12,360 --> 00:22:14,490
it's a just so story,

557
00:22:14,490 --> 00:22:19,200
but someone or some group must
have inhaled the smoke from

558
00:22:19,200 --> 00:22:22,710
the tobacco plant or put the dried leaves

559
00:22:22,710 --> 00:22:26,040
of the tobacco plant
against some mucosal tissue,

560
00:22:26,040 --> 00:22:27,930
and you know the different
mucosal linings of their body

561
00:22:27,930 --> 00:22:31,170
by which substances can
pass through, that's right.

562
00:22:31,170 --> 00:22:34,500
Any of the mucosal soft
lining tissues of the body

563
00:22:34,500 --> 00:22:36,210
will allow certain substances,

564
00:22:36,210 --> 00:22:38,010
not all certain substances to pass in.

565
00:22:38,010 --> 00:22:40,356
That's why people can put
tobacco in their mouth

566
00:22:40,356 --> 00:22:41,189
and a certain amount of nicotine makes it

567
00:22:41,189 --> 00:22:42,022
into the bloodstream,

568
00:22:42,022 --> 00:22:43,334
put tobacco up their nose,

569
00:22:43,334 --> 00:22:45,420
certain amount of nicotine
gets into the bloodstream.

570
00:22:45,420 --> 00:22:48,150
I haven't heard of people
putting tobacco in other orifices

571
00:22:48,150 --> 00:22:49,710
of their body containing mucosal tissue.

572
00:22:49,710 --> 00:22:51,750
And I'm certainly not
suggesting people do that,

573
00:22:51,750 --> 00:22:52,800
but you get the idea

574
00:22:52,800 --> 00:22:54,870
and how nicotine gets from these plants,

575
00:22:54,870 --> 00:22:57,543
these dried leaves into the bloodstream.

576
00:22:58,440 --> 00:23:02,310
Burning tobacco leads
to a heat induced change

577
00:23:02,310 --> 00:23:04,050
in the availability of nicotine.

578
00:23:04,050 --> 00:23:06,390
And this is why smoking tobacco

579
00:23:06,390 --> 00:23:10,670
or vaping tobacco,
simply by heating it up,

580
00:23:10,670 --> 00:23:12,990
allows the nicotine to be
liberated and go into the

581
00:23:12,990 --> 00:23:15,360
bloodstream simply by
inhaling it into the lungs.

582
00:23:15,360 --> 00:23:18,150
We will get back to smoking
of various kinds later.

583
00:23:18,150 --> 00:23:22,410
But right now let's just keep
our attention on how nicotine

584
00:23:22,410 --> 00:23:25,890
is pulled from these plants
and into the human body.

585
00:23:25,890 --> 00:23:29,520
Now whether by inhalation
or whether or not by placing

586
00:23:29,520 --> 00:23:31,770
in contact with the
mucosal tissue of the mouth

587
00:23:31,770 --> 00:23:36,060
or other mucosal containing
orifice of the body,

588
00:23:36,060 --> 00:23:38,340
the nicotine then gets
into the bloodstream.

589
00:23:38,340 --> 00:23:40,320
And once it's in the bloodstream,

590
00:23:40,320 --> 00:23:42,840
it only exerts its
effects because it binds

591
00:23:42,840 --> 00:23:46,233
to certain so-called nicotinic receptors.

592
00:23:47,560 --> 00:23:49,050
So the nicotinic receptors

593
00:23:49,050 --> 00:23:51,840
are of the acetylcholinergic variety.

594
00:23:51,840 --> 00:23:54,120
I know this is a lot to think
about and a lot to hear if you

595
00:23:54,120 --> 00:23:56,100
haven't heard about this, but
it's actually quite simple.

596
00:23:56,100 --> 00:23:57,720
Anyone can understand this.

597
00:23:57,720 --> 00:24:01,170
Acetylcholine is a molecule,

598
00:24:01,170 --> 00:24:05,760
a chemical that is that's
released in the brain and body.

599
00:24:05,760 --> 00:24:07,680
And when it binds to receptors,

600
00:24:07,680 --> 00:24:09,690
that is little parking spots on cells,

601
00:24:09,690 --> 00:24:11,910
it changes the way those cells behave.

602
00:24:11,910 --> 00:24:13,890
Those cells can increase their activity

603
00:24:13,890 --> 00:24:14,940
and release other chemicals.

604
00:24:14,940 --> 00:24:16,260
They can become electrically active,

605
00:24:16,260 --> 00:24:19,140
they can do any number
of different things.

606
00:24:19,140 --> 00:24:21,690
When we ingest nicotine,

607
00:24:21,690 --> 00:24:23,583
it gets into the bloodstream
and eventually some of that

608
00:24:23,583 --> 00:24:26,130
will get into the brain and
some of it gets into the body.

609
00:24:26,130 --> 00:24:27,660
And in both of the brain and body,

610
00:24:27,660 --> 00:24:30,720
there are the so-called nicotinic
acetylcholine receptors.

611
00:24:30,720 --> 00:24:34,290
Now the so-called family,
and indeed they are a family,

612
00:24:34,290 --> 00:24:36,870
this is how we refer
to groups of receptors

613
00:24:36,870 --> 00:24:40,800
of related design and genetic
background just like humans.

614
00:24:40,800 --> 00:24:43,620
You have a family of these
acetylcholine receptors

615
00:24:43,620 --> 00:24:44,940
that are of the nicotinic variety.

616
00:24:44,940 --> 00:24:46,920
So maybe on one street
in your neighborhood,

617
00:24:46,920 --> 00:24:48,480
you know the Joneses and another street,

618
00:24:48,480 --> 00:24:51,000
you know the Chows and another
street, well in your body,

619
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:53,160
you have the nicotinic
acetylcholine receptors,

620
00:24:53,160 --> 00:24:53,993
and then you have the so-called

621
00:24:53,993 --> 00:24:56,160
muscarinic acetylcholine receptors.

622
00:24:56,160 --> 00:24:57,210
Today it's really simple.

623
00:24:57,210 --> 00:24:59,550
Nicotine only binds to the
nicotinic acetylcholine

624
00:24:59,550 --> 00:25:01,680
receptors and there are
a bunch of different ones

625
00:25:01,680 --> 00:25:03,210
on a bunch of different tissues.

626
00:25:03,210 --> 00:25:07,350
And the differences in those
receptors dictate what sorts of

627
00:25:07,350 --> 00:25:11,430
effects the nicotine will
have on those tissues.

628
00:25:11,430 --> 00:25:13,050
So let's talk about
what those effects are,

629
00:25:13,050 --> 00:25:15,540
and let's do that by dividing
the effects of nicotine

630
00:25:15,540 --> 00:25:17,130
into effects on the brain,

631
00:25:17,130 --> 00:25:19,650
so everything from the
neck up, and on the body,

632
00:25:19,650 --> 00:25:22,140
the so-called central nervous
system and the periphery.

633
00:25:22,140 --> 00:25:23,550
Although I want to point
out that your spinal cord

634
00:25:23,550 --> 00:25:24,780
is part of the central nervous system.

635
00:25:24,780 --> 00:25:27,360
So in fairness to the reality,

636
00:25:27,360 --> 00:25:30,420
your brain and spinal cord are
all central nervous system.

637
00:25:30,420 --> 00:25:32,910
Everything else is
considered the periphery.

638
00:25:32,910 --> 00:25:34,410
Now there are a lot of different nicotinic

639
00:25:34,410 --> 00:25:35,730
acetylcholine receptors,

640
00:25:35,730 --> 00:25:38,340
but for those of you that
want to know, you aficionados,

641
00:25:38,340 --> 00:25:40,770
or if you're ultra curious about this,

642
00:25:40,770 --> 00:25:44,520
the main effects of nicotine
in the brain are mediated

643
00:25:44,520 --> 00:25:47,010
by nicotine binding to the so-called

644
00:25:47,010 --> 00:25:49,770
alpha four beta two receptor.

645
00:25:49,770 --> 00:25:52,140
Alpha four beta two receptor.

646
00:25:52,140 --> 00:25:54,570
Even if you don't care
about receptor subtypes,

647
00:25:54,570 --> 00:25:56,430
that's going to come up
later when we discuss

648
00:25:56,430 --> 00:25:59,370
why nicotine suppresses appetite.

649
00:25:59,370 --> 00:26:02,130
In fact, one of the major
reasons why people don't want

650
00:26:02,130 --> 00:26:04,770
to quit smoking, or they quit smoking

651
00:26:04,770 --> 00:26:06,570
or another form of ingesting nicotine,

652
00:26:06,570 --> 00:26:08,130
and then they relapse,

653
00:26:08,130 --> 00:26:11,550
they go back to smoking or
ingesting nicotine in some other

654
00:26:11,550 --> 00:26:15,840
way is because indeed nicotine
will increase metabolism

655
00:26:15,840 --> 00:26:18,240
and reduce hunger in large part

656
00:26:18,240 --> 00:26:20,880
by binding to this alpha
four beta two receptor

657
00:26:20,880 --> 00:26:21,960
in a particular area of the brain.

658
00:26:21,960 --> 00:26:23,100
We're going to return
to that in a little bit,

659
00:26:23,100 --> 00:26:26,070
but if you've ever heard that
nicotine kills the appetite,

660
00:26:26,070 --> 00:26:27,450
indeed it does.

661
00:26:27,450 --> 00:26:29,629
It's not the behavior of smoking itself.

662
00:26:29,629 --> 00:26:30,462
It's not because you
always have a cigarette

663
00:26:30,462 --> 00:26:32,070
in your mouth that you're
not eating more food.

664
00:26:32,070 --> 00:26:34,260
Although I suppose that
might be a minor effect.

665
00:26:34,260 --> 00:26:37,530
There are direct effects of
nicotine on both appetite,

666
00:26:37,530 --> 00:26:39,960
that is, it reduces
appetite and direct effects

667
00:26:39,960 --> 00:26:40,970
on metabolism, that is,

668
00:26:40,970 --> 00:26:43,020
it increases metabolism
through its effects

669
00:26:43,020 --> 00:26:44,610
on some other areas of the brain and body

670
00:26:44,610 --> 00:26:45,687
we'll talk about in a moment.

671
00:26:45,687 --> 00:26:47,250
Now within the brain,

672
00:26:47,250 --> 00:26:51,270
nicotine binds to this
alpha four beta two receptor

673
00:26:51,270 --> 00:26:52,920
in various locations in the brain.

674
00:26:52,920 --> 00:26:56,070
And there are three and maybe
a fourth that we'll talk about

675
00:26:56,070 --> 00:26:59,580
neurochemical effects of
nicotine after you ingest it.

676
00:26:59,580 --> 00:27:00,660
First things first,

677
00:27:00,660 --> 00:27:01,950
when you ingest nicotine

678
00:27:01,950 --> 00:27:05,400
by smoking nicotine containing tobacco,

679
00:27:05,400 --> 00:27:09,870
or if you place tobacco in
contact with the mucosal lining

680
00:27:09,870 --> 00:27:12,180
of the nasal passages of the mouth,

681
00:27:12,180 --> 00:27:16,170
takes about two to 15
minutes for that nicotine

682
00:27:16,170 --> 00:27:17,003
to enter the bloodstream.

683
00:27:17,003 --> 00:27:20,490
Smoking hits the bloodstream
faster, vaping even faster,

684
00:27:20,490 --> 00:27:24,420
I should mention for a
variety of reasons and placing

685
00:27:24,420 --> 00:27:27,420
tobacco directly in contact
with the mucosal lining

686
00:27:27,420 --> 00:27:28,800
is going to be the slowest.

687
00:27:28,800 --> 00:27:29,970
Now as I mentioned before,

688
00:27:29,970 --> 00:27:32,850
nicotine gets into the bloodstream
and then because nicotine

689
00:27:32,850 --> 00:27:36,690
can pass through the so-called
blood brain barrier, the BBB,

690
00:27:36,690 --> 00:27:39,090
which is basically a
fence around the brain,

691
00:27:39,090 --> 00:27:41,340
because it can pass through
the blood brain barrier,

692
00:27:41,340 --> 00:27:43,560
it's going to have very
rapid effects on the brain

693
00:27:43,560 --> 00:27:45,660
in these four major categories

694
00:27:45,660 --> 00:27:48,870
of neurochemicals and neural circuits.

695
00:27:48,870 --> 00:27:52,110
The first of those categories,
this is a very important one,

696
00:27:52,110 --> 00:27:54,210
this is one that was brought
up in the episode on dopamine,

697
00:27:54,210 --> 00:27:55,920
motivation, and drive.

698
00:27:55,920 --> 00:27:57,240
And I think not just all scientists,

699
00:27:57,240 --> 00:28:00,240
but all human beings should
know that within their brain,

700
00:28:00,240 --> 00:28:05,240
they have what is called the
mesolimbic reward pathway.

701
00:28:05,340 --> 00:28:07,500
The mesolimbic reward pathway
if you just want to call it,

702
00:28:07,500 --> 00:28:11,070
the dopamine reward pathway
is, as the name suggests,

703
00:28:11,070 --> 00:28:12,990
a set of connections between a brain area

704
00:28:12,990 --> 00:28:14,520
called the ventral tegmental area.

705
00:28:14,520 --> 00:28:16,500
You don't have to remember
the names of these things,

706
00:28:16,500 --> 00:28:18,780
of course, but if you
want to, that's fine too.

707
00:28:18,780 --> 00:28:20,130
The ventral tegmental area

708
00:28:20,130 --> 00:28:22,860
or VTA connects to another area called

709
00:28:22,860 --> 00:28:24,900
the nucleus accumbens.

710
00:28:24,900 --> 00:28:26,460
Now here's what's very important.

711
00:28:26,460 --> 00:28:30,450
Nicotine triggers the release of dopamine

712
00:28:30,450 --> 00:28:31,680
from the nucleus accumbens.

713
00:28:31,680 --> 00:28:34,770
This is what gives nicotine
its rewarding properties.

714
00:28:34,770 --> 00:28:36,150
It increases motivation.

715
00:28:36,150 --> 00:28:39,270
It tends to give a not so subtle,

716
00:28:39,270 --> 00:28:41,640
but very transient increase in feelings

717
00:28:41,640 --> 00:28:44,760
of wellbeing and alertness and motivation.

718
00:28:44,760 --> 00:28:46,800
And that's because of
the increase in dopamine

719
00:28:46,800 --> 00:28:50,583
caused by nicotine directly
within the nucleus accumbens.

720
00:28:52,050 --> 00:28:55,320
Nicotine also triggers the
release of certain neurochemicals

721
00:28:55,320 --> 00:28:57,510
from the ventral tegmental area itself.

722
00:28:57,510 --> 00:28:59,850
And those impinge on nucleus accumbens

723
00:28:59,850 --> 00:29:02,220
and increase dopamine levels further.

724
00:29:02,220 --> 00:29:05,100
This is what makes the rewarding
properties or sometimes

725
00:29:05,100 --> 00:29:07,830
referred to as the reinforcing
properties of nicotine

726
00:29:07,830 --> 00:29:08,730
so powerful.

727
00:29:08,730 --> 00:29:13,110
This is why so many billions
of people ingest nicotine

728
00:29:13,110 --> 00:29:14,130
in one form or another.

729
00:29:14,130 --> 00:29:18,120
It's also why nicotine is so hard to quit

730
00:29:18,120 --> 00:29:20,850
because there's a potent
increase in dopamine

731
00:29:20,850 --> 00:29:23,100
from multiple neural circuit pathways

732
00:29:23,100 --> 00:29:26,340
within this mesolimbic reward circuitry.

733
00:29:26,340 --> 00:29:29,070
Now within the mesolimbic
reward circuitry,

734
00:29:29,070 --> 00:29:29,970
there's an interesting feature.

735
00:29:29,970 --> 00:29:32,700
There are accelerators
that essentially push out

736
00:29:32,700 --> 00:29:34,920
more dopamine, get more dopamine released,

737
00:29:34,920 --> 00:29:37,830
and there are breaks of the
so-called GABAergic variety.

738
00:29:37,830 --> 00:29:39,960
GABA's an inhibitory neurotransmitter.

739
00:29:39,960 --> 00:29:42,360
You don't need to know too much
about it to just understand

740
00:29:42,360 --> 00:29:45,660
that nicotine both increases dopamine,

741
00:29:45,660 --> 00:29:49,380
but also decreases the activity of GABA.

742
00:29:49,380 --> 00:29:51,480
And so this is like
pushing on the accelerator

743
00:29:51,480 --> 00:29:54,690
for dopamine, but also removing the brake.

744
00:29:54,690 --> 00:29:57,960
So there's a two pronged
effect of nicotine

745
00:29:57,960 --> 00:30:01,320
on reinforcement reward
dopamine related pathways,

746
00:30:01,320 --> 00:30:03,990
the feel good motivation pathways.

747
00:30:03,990 --> 00:30:08,520
And that is an increase in
dopamine and a decrease in GABA.

748
00:30:08,520 --> 00:30:09,353
And again,

749
00:30:09,353 --> 00:30:11,370
that's all mediated through
this mesolimbic reward pathway,

750
00:30:11,370 --> 00:30:13,290
involving the ventral tegmental area

751
00:30:13,290 --> 00:30:14,700
and the nucleus accumbens.

752
00:30:14,700 --> 00:30:15,900
So if you can conceptualize

753
00:30:15,900 --> 00:30:18,300
even just 5% of what I just told you,

754
00:30:18,300 --> 00:30:21,300
or even if you can just remember
nicotine increases dopamine

755
00:30:21,300 --> 00:30:22,520
and that's why it feels so good,

756
00:30:22,520 --> 00:30:24,690
it makes you want more of it,

757
00:30:24,690 --> 00:30:27,690
you will have everything you
need to know in mind in order

758
00:30:27,690 --> 00:30:32,690
to understand both why
nicotine is so highly used,

759
00:30:32,760 --> 00:30:35,220
and indeed abused, why
it's so hard to quit,

760
00:30:35,220 --> 00:30:36,780
and that will point to avenues

761
00:30:36,780 --> 00:30:39,120
as to how to quit or reduce intake.

